Excitation of SOMs by horizontal axons\
The above observations open two fundamental questions: First, what are the cortical circuits that enable SOMs, in contrast to other cortical neurons, not to be suppressed but rather 
\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
facilitated
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 by large stimuli? Second, do SOMs contribute to size tuning in V1? Both questions are addressed below.\
The two predominant excitatory inputs to layer 2/3 are vertically ascending axons from layer 4 and horizontal projecting axons from layer 2/3. Are SOMs equally excited by these two inputs? We recorded from layer 2/3 pyramidal cells (PCs), SOMs and PVs in coronal slices of V1 and selectively photo-activated (light ramp of 2s duration; 480 nm light) layer 4 excitatory cells that conditionally expressed Channelrhodopsin-2 (ChR2; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#SD2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Suppl. Fig 4}}). Layer 4 photo-stimulation generated excitatory charges in SOMs that were only 17 \'b1 5% (n=8) of those in simultaneously recorded PCs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 2a}}); in contrast, excitatory charges generated in PVs were 250 \'b1 39% (n=8) of those generated in simultaneously recorded PCs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 2b}}). These results were corroborated through ChR2-assisted circuit mapping {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#R29"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
29}} ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#SD2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Suppl. Fig. 5}}). Thus, ascending layer 4 axon provide little excitation to SOMs. In striking contrast, photo-stimulation of layer 2/3 PCs (2 s light ramp duration) that selectively expressed ChR2 (see methods {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#R30"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
30}}) produced substantial excitation of layer 2/3 SOMs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig 2d}}): the excitation that SOMs received was in fact significantly larger than that received by simultaneously recorded PCs (241 \'b1 85%; n=7; p<0.05; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 2e}}; we selectively recorded from those PCs not expressing ChR2 in order to avoid contamination with photocurrents). Furthermore, while photo-stimulation of horizontal layer 2/3 projections was accompanied by strong disynaptic inhibition in PCs, only very little inhibition was recorded in SOMs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 2e}}; the ratio of excitation to the sum of excitation and inhibition (E/(E+I)) was 0.11 \'b1 0.01 (n=10) in PCs versus 0.59 \'b1 0.06 (n= 11) in SOMs; p<0.05, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 2f}}). Thus, these results show that while layer 2/3 pyramidal and PVs receive substantial excitatory drive from ascending layer 4 axons, the main excitation to layer 2/3 SOMs are horizontal axons of layer 2/3.\
