Size-dependent excitation of SOMs\
To ascertain that these horizontal axons are indeed responsible for the size-dependent recruitment of SOMs, we took advantage of the retinotopic organization of V1; we reasoned that because progressively larger visual stimuli presented 
\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
in vivo
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 will result in a progressively larger visually activated area in V1 we could approximate this expansion of activity by directly photo-stimulating progressively larger areas of V1. We performed loose patch recordings from SOMs in coronal slices of V1 expressing ChR2 in layer 2/3 PCs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F3/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig 3a}}). The firing rate of SOMs increased as a function of the size of the light spot (range of sizes 180\'96900 \'b5m), similar to their increase in firing rate 
\i \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
in vivo
\i0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 with increasing visual stimulus size ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F3/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 3a,b}}). Consistent with the increase in firing rate, the synaptic excitation received by SOMs increased with increasing light spot size ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F3/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 3a,b}}). If SOM dendrites were to span areas similar to the largest light-spot diameter, the progressive increase in firing rate with spot size could simply result from the direct photo-stimulation of synapses on the dendritic arborization of the recorded SOM. This was however not the case because even the smallest light spot used (180 \'b5m diameter), generating only ~25% of the maximal firing rate, covered already more than 95% of the entire SOM dendritic arborization ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F3/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 3b}}, see methods). Thus, the increase in SOM firing rate with spot size results from the recruitment of progressively more distant L2/3 PCs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F3/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 3b}}, see methods). Furthermore, cutting horizontal axons with two vertical cuts through layer 2/3 on each side of the recorded SOMs (320 \'b125 \'b5m between cuts, centered on the cell; n=10; note that the distance between the cuts is larger than the horizontal dendritic extent of SOMs ) prevented the increase in firing rate with stimuli larger than the distance between the two cuts ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#SD2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Suppl. Fig. 6}}). Thus, by using horizontal layer 2/3 projections as their main excitatory drive, SOMs are recruited as a function of the activated V1 area, that is they sum activity in visual space.\
