Suppl. Fig. 1}}) the firing rate of SOMs was reduced ten fold (from 26 \'b1 2 Hz, n=8 to 2.7\'b1 0.4 Hz, n= 10), much more than that of single units or PVs ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#SD2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Suppl. Fig. 1}}). To directly test for the involvement of SOMs in surround suppression we conditionally expressed the light-sensitive hyperpolarizing opsin archaerhodopsin (Arch) in V1 using viral injection of a flexed Arch vector into SOM-Cre mice (71 \'b1 2% of cells infected, n = 4 animals, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F4/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 4b}} and see methods). Illumination of the cortical surface efficiently reduced the visually evoked activity of Arch-expressing layer 2/3 SOMs (80 \'b1 1% suppression, n = 4, p<0.05; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107#SD2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Supp. Fig. 7}}),. To determine the impact of SOMs on size tuning in layer 2/3 we performed extracellular recordings as described above and alternated control trials (visual stimulus only) with trials in which SOMs were photo-hyperpolarized ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F4/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fig. 4}}). Photo-hyperpolarization of SOMs significantly reduced surround suppression of layer 2/3 neurons by 30 \'b1 10% (n=28; p < 0.00022, paired signed rank test; Fig.4c-e; photo-hyperpolarization of SOMs had no significant effect on baseline firing rates \uc0\u8722 9\'b117%; n=13; p>0.18). Nearly all units (25/28) showed a decrease in SI ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC3621107/figure/F4/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
